### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

I have a `ControlValueAccessor` implementation to handle file inputs. It is fairly straightforward.

```typescript
export class Example implements ControlValueAccessor {
  @HostListener('change', ['$event.target.files ?? null']) public executeOnChangeHandler(value: null | FileList): void {
    this.#onChangeHandler?.(value);
  }

  public writeValue(value: null): void {
    this.#renderer.setProperty(this.#elementRef.nativeElement, 'value', value);
  }

  // ... the rest of the implementation
}
```

In case the file input gets interacted with before hydration the `'change'` events will be captured by event replay. But my `'change'` event listener reads the most recent `files` property on the input element which got meanwhile reset by `writeValue()` by the time the captured event gets replayed.

As a result event replay is not working as expected and the form field basically gets reset during hydration as described in #53917.

### Proposed solution

Since Angular already supports selecting function arguments with an expression I would like to propose using that expression to cache the function arguments when capturing an event.

In case of my example the flow would be like this:

- The prerendered page loads with a pristine file input.
- The user selects a file.
- Event replay captures the `'change'` event **and evaluates the function argument selector `('$event.target.files ?? null')`**. It will cache the result.
- The component taking care of the file input hydrates. It calls `writeValue()` with the initial value.
- Event replay invokes the `'change'` event handler with the previously cached arguments.

### Alternatives considered

For now I'm using an internal boolean flag to avoid setting the initial value.

```typescript
export class Example implements ControlValueAccessor {
  #wroteFirstValue = false;

  @HostListener('change', ['$event.target.files ?? null']) public executeOnChangeHandler(value: null | FileList): void {
    this.#onChangeHandler?.(value);
  }

  public writeValue(value: null): void {
    if (this.#wroteFirstValue) {
      this.#renderer.setProperty(this.#elementRef.nativeElement, 'value', value);
    } else {
      this.#wroteFirstValue = true;
    }
  }

  // ... the rest of the implementation
}
```

But this only works because the `ControlValueAccessor` implementation knows it deals with a prerendered file input and the initial value is actually the native default value. I would prefer to have a `ControlValueAccessor` implementation which doesn't need to know anything about the outside conditions.

